  <title>Capstone Problem Set</title>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Instructions</title>
        <p>
            Prior to beginning the Capstone Problem Set, please read the instructions carefully on Canvas. 
            In particular, note the following key elements:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        You are <em>permitted</em> two (2) collaborators. Here, <q>collaboration</q> refers to thought-partnership in solving problems. 
                        The solutions you submit should clearly indicated your name and the name of your collaborators (as appropriate). 
                        The written work you turn is expected to be your own; if any portion of your work appears to have been generated by someone or something other than yourself, it may be submitted for plagiarism investigation. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Unlike a standard problem, <alert>there is no grace period</alert>. 
                        The capstone is due exactly as indicated on Canvas/gradescope. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>
<problem>
        <title>(Problem 1)</title>
        <introduction>
      <p> Let <m>T:\mathbb R^5\to\mathbb R^4</m> be the transformation with standard matrix <m>A</m>, where <me>A=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 2 &amp; -4 &amp; 12 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; -3 &amp; 9 \\ 2 &amp; 4 &amp; 3 &amp; -4 &amp; 13 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; -3 &amp; 6 \end{array}\right]\sim\left[\begin{array}{ccccc} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; -2 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 3 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; -2 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \end{array}\right]=\mathrm{RREF}\,A</me> </p>
      <p> Answer each of the following questions, providing a detailed enough explanation that it's clear your solution isn't a guess. </p>
    </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p> Find the solution set of the following system. <me>\begin{matrix} x_{1} &amp; + &amp; 2 \, x_{2} &amp; + &amp; 2 \, x_{3} &amp; - &amp; 4 \, x_{4} &amp; + &amp; 12 \, x_{5} &amp; = &amp; 0 \\ &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; x_{3} &amp; - &amp; 3 \, x_{4} &amp; + &amp; 9 \, x_{5} &amp; = &amp; 0 \\ 2 \, x_{1} &amp; + &amp; 4 \, x_{2} &amp; + &amp; 3 \, x_{3} &amp; - &amp; 4 \, x_{4} &amp; + &amp; 13 \, x_{5} &amp; = &amp; 0 \\ &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; - &amp; 3 \, x_{4} &amp; + &amp; 6 \, x_{5} &amp; = &amp; 0 \\ \end{matrix}</me> </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p> Explain why the set <m>S=\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 0 \\ 2 \\ 0 \end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 0 \\ 4 \\ 0 \end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \\ 3 \\ 0 \end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{c} -4 \\ -3 \\ -4 \\ -3 \end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{c} 12 \\ 9 \\ 13 \\ 6 \end{array}\right] \right\}</m> is or is not a basis for <m>\mathbb R^4</m> by discussing spanning and independence. </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p> Explain why the collection <m>\left\{ x^{3} + 2 \, x , 2 \, x^{3} + 4 \, x , 2 \, x^{3} + x^{2} + 3 \, x , -4 \, x^{3} - 3 \, x^{2} - 4 \, x - 3 , 12 \, x^{3} + 9 \, x^{2} + 13 \, x + 6 \right\}</m> of polynomials is linearly independent or linearly dependent by discussing two isomorphic vector spaces. </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p> Explain why <m>T</m> is or is not surjective, and is or is not injective, by inspecting rows and columns of an appropriate matrix. </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p> Find bases for the image and kernel of <m>T</m>, and use them to verify the rank-nullity theorem for <m>T</m>. </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>(Problem 2)</title>
        <introduction>
        <p>
            Let <m>R_\theta\colon\IR^2\to\IR^2</m> denote the linear transformation given by rotating vectors counter-clockwise about the origin through an angle of <m>\theta</m>, as measured from the positive <m>x_1</m>-axis. 
        </p>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>T_\theta</m> denote the standard matrix for <m>R_\theta</m>. 
                    Explain and demonstrate how to calculate <m>T_\theta</m> for every angle <m>\theta</m>. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Suppose that <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are two angles. 
                    <em>Without calculating the products explicitly</em> (i.e, using geometric reasoning), explain why <m>T_{\alpha}T_\beta=T_{\alpha+\beta}</m>. 
                    Conclude that <m>T_\alpha,T_\beta</m> commute with each other; i.e., <m>T_{\alpha}T_\beta=T_\beta T_\alpha</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Now calculuate the product <m>T_\alpha T_\beta</m> explicitly. 
                    Explain and demonstrate how to use this calculation to prove the following trigonometric identities:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\cos(\alpha+\beta)=\cos(\alpha)\cos(\beta)-\sin(\alpha)\sin(\beta)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\sin(\alpha+\beta)=\sin(\alpha)\cos(\beta)+\cos(\alpha)\sin(\beta)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        </introduction>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>(Problem 3)</title>
        <introduction>
        <p>
            Let <m>A</m> denote the following <m>2\times 3</m> matrix:
            <me>A=\begin{bmatrix}1&amp;-1&amp;7\\1&amp;2&amp;-2\end{bmatrix}.</me>
            Then: <m>X\in M_{3,2}</m> is an arbitrary <m>3\times 2</m> matrix, the product <m>AX</m> will always be a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix; that is, <m>AX\in M_{2,2}</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>    
            Now let <m>T\colon M_{3,2}\to M_{2,2}</m> denote the transformation given by the rule <m>T(X)=AX</m>.
        </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Calculate <m>T\left(\left[\begin{array}{cc}1&amp;1\\0&amp;-1\\2&amp;3\end{array}\right]\right)</m> and <m>T\left(\left[\begin{array}{cc}x_1&amp;x_2\\y_1&amp;y_2\\z_1&amp;z_2\end{array}\right]\right)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <em>Using properties of matrix multiplication and addition</em>, explain why <m>T\colon M_{3,2}\to M_{2,2}</m> is a linear map. 
                    <em>You may assume that matrix multiplication is associative and distributive.</em>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Explain and demonstrate how to calculuate a basis for <m>\ker(T)</m>; in particular, what is the dimension of <m>\ker(T)</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the dimension of <m>\textrm{im}(T)</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>(Problem 4)</title>
        <introduction>
        <p>
            Eigenvalues/vectors can be used to help explore the underlying geometry of a linear transformation. 
            In this structured exploration, your main task is to justify the given claims using facts/concepts we've covered in class. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Let <m>T\colon\IR^2\to\IR^2</m> denote the transformation of the Euclidean plane whose standard matrix is as follows:
            <me>
                A=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
                \frac{9}{14} &amp; -\frac{1}{14} \\
                -\frac{1}{21} &amp; \frac{11}{21}\end{array}\right].
            </me>
            
        </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\vec{v}=\left[\begin{array}{c}1\\2\end{array}\right]</m> and <m>\vec{w}=\left[\begin{array}{c}-3\\1\end{array}\right]</m>.
                    Explain and demonstrate how to <em>verify</em> that <m>\vec{v}</m> is an eigenvector for <m>T</m> with eigenvalue <m>\alpha=\frac{1}{2}</m> and that <m>\vec{w}</m> is an eigenvector of <m>T</m> with eigenvalue <m>\beta=\frac{2}{3}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Justify the following claim: <q>If we repeatedly apply <m>A</m> to <m>\vec{v}</m> or <m>\vec{w}</m>, the output vectors will get closer and closer to <m>\vec{0}</m>. 
                    That is, if we look at the sequence of vectors <m>\vec{v},A\vec{v},A(A\vec{v}),A(A(A\vec{v})),\dots</m> the vectors get closer and closer to  <m>\vec{0}</m> and likewise for <m>\vec{w}</m>.</q>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Explain why the set <m>\{\vec{v},\vec{w}\}</m> is a basis of <m>\IR^2</m>. 
                    Then, building on your reasoning in (b), justify the following claim: <q>If <m>\vec{u}</m> is <em>any</em> vector in <m>\IR^2</m>, then repeatedly applying the transformation <m>A</m> to <m>\vec{u}</m> will produce vectors that are closer and closer to <m>\vec{0}</m>. </q>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </problem>


